NO. The proposed patch removes the critical optimization and correctness mechanism of tracking occupied columns and diagonals using sets, which was essential to correctly prune invalid queen placements. By eliminating these sets and relying solely on scanning the board for conflicts, the patched code loses the ability to efficiently and accurately detect diagonal conflicts, especially those involving the sums and differences of row and column indices. This reversion to a purely board-scan approach not only reintroduces the original bug—where valid solutions are incorrectly rejected due to conflating two diagonal families—but also significantly degrades performance by increasing the complexity of safety checks. Furthermore, the patch does not address the root cause of the bug related to the shared occupied_diagonals set conflating two distinct diagonal directions; instead, it removes the diagonal caching entirely, which is a step backward. Therefore, the patch fails to fix the bug and undermines the algorithm's correctness and efficiency.
